<div style="display: none"><ix:header><ix:references><link:schemaRef xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="gme-20250201.xsd"/></ix:references></ix:header></div><div><div><div style="line-height:normal;display: inline;"><div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto"><div style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">Codes of Ethics </div></div></div></div><div style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We have adopted a Code of Ethics for Senior Financial and Executive Officers that is applicable to our Chief Executive Officer, Principal Financial Officer, Principal Accounting Officer, any Executive Vice President, and any Senior Vice President or Vice President employed in a finance or accounting role and any managing director or finance director of all our foreign subsidiaries. We have also adopted a Code of Standards, Ethics and Conduct applicable to all of our associates and <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-employee</div> directors. The Code of Ethics for Senior Financial and Executive Officers and the Code of Standards, Ethics and Conduct are available on our website at <div style="font-style: normal; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="font-style:italic;display:inline;"><div style="font-family:ARIAL;color:#1e3aff;display:inline;"><div style="text-decoration: underline; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">http://investor.gamestop.com/corporate-governance</div></div> </div></div>and are available in print to any stockholder who requests them in writing to our Secretary, GameStop Corp., 625 Westport Parkway, Grapevine, Texas 76051. In accordance with SEC rules, we intend to disclose any amendment (other than any technical, administrative or other <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-substantive</div> amendment) to either of the above Codes, or any waiver of any provision thereof with respect to certain specified officers listed above, on our website at <div style="font-style: normal; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="font-style:italic;display:inline;"><div style="font-family:ARIAL;color:#1e3aff;display:inline;"><div style="text-decoration: underline; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">http://investor.gamestop.com/corporate-governance</div></div> </div></div>within four business days following such amendment or waiver. </div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">Clawback Policy </div></div></div></div><div style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">To comply with SEC and NYSE rules, during fiscal 2023 we adopted a new clawback policy, a copy of which is filed with the SEC as an exhibit to our Annual Report, to provide for the recovery of any erroneously awarded incentive-based compensation, as defined under SEC and NYSE rules, in the event we are required to prepare an accounting restatement due to our material noncompliance with any financial reporting requirement under the federal securities laws. In the event that recovery is required, the Board will review and recover reasonably promptly all erroneously awarded incentive-based compensation awarded to or earned by our officers during the three-year period prior to the date we are required to prepare an accounting restatement. Recovery will be required on a &#8220;no fault&#8221; basis, without regard to whether any misconduct occurred and without regard to whether an executive officer was responsible for the erroneous financial statements. In addition, the clawback policy allows us to recover any incentive-based compensation received by an executive officer during certain periods to the extent the Board determines in its good faith judgment that any financial reporting measures or other operating metrics were achieved in whole or part as a result of fraud or other misconduct on the part of such executive officer, or fraud or other misconduct of other employees of the Company of which such executive officer had knowledge, whether or not such conduct results in a restatement of Company financial statements. </div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">Equity Ownership Policy </div></div></div></div><div style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Board believes that it is important for each executive officer and <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-employee</div> director to have a financial stake in the Company to help align the executive officer&#8217;s and <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-employee</div> director&#8217;s interests with those of our stockholders. To that end, we have an equity ownership policy requiring that each executive officer and <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-employee</div> director maintain ownership of common stock with a value of at least the following: </div><div style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="text-align:start; BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;width:100%;border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto">
<tr>
<td style="width:54%"/>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:0%"/>
<td style="width:30pt;white-space:nowrap"/>
<td/>
<td/>
<td style="width:30pt;white-space:nowrap"/></tr>
<tr style="font-size:1pt;background-color:#e2231a">
<td style="height:1.5pt"/>
<td colspan="5" style="height:1.5pt"/></tr>
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt;background-color:#e2231a">
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;vertical-align:bottom"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; text-indent: 0.5em; font-size: 8pt; font-family: ARIAL; line-height: normal;"><div style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;"><div style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">Executive Officer or <div style="white-space:nowrap;display:inline;">Non-employee</div> Director</div></div></div></div></div></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom"/>
<td colspan="4" style="padding-bottom:3pt ;vertical-align:bottom;text-align:center"><div style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;"><div style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">&#8195;&#8195;&#8195;&#8195;&#8195;&#8195;Fiscal&#160;2024&#160;Stock&#160;Ownership&#160;Guidelines&#8195;&#8195;&#8195;&#8195;&#8195;&#8195;</div></div></div></div></td></tr>

<td style="height:3pt"/>
<td colspan="5" style="height:3pt"/></tr>
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;background-color:#d6d6d6">
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;vertical-align:top"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-left: 0.44em; font-size: 9pt; font-family: ARIAL; line-height: normal;">Chief Executive Officer</div></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom"/>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom"/>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom;text-align:center">5&#160;times&#160;base&#160;salary</td>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom"/></tr>
<tr style="font-size:1pt">
<td style="height:3pt"/>
<td colspan="5" style="height:3pt"/></tr>
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt">
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;vertical-align:top"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-left: 0.44em; font-size: 9pt; font-family: ARIAL; line-height: normal;">Named Executive Officer</div></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom"/>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom"/>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom;text-align:center">3 times base salary</td>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom"/></tr>
<tr style="font-size:1pt;background-color:#d6d6d6">
<td style="height:3pt"/>
<td colspan="5" style="height:3pt"/></tr>
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;background-color:#d6d6d6">
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;vertical-align:top"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-left: 0.44em; font-size: 9pt; font-family: ARIAL; line-height: normal;"><div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">Non-employee</div> Director</div></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom"/>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom"/>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom;text-align:center">$275,000</td>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom"/></tr></table><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">New executive officers or <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-employee</div> directors are given a period of five (5)&#160;years to attain full compliance with these requirements. These requirements will be reduced by 50% for executive officers after the executive officer reaches the age of 62 in order to facilitate appropriate financial planning. </div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">For purposes of these determinations, (i)&#160;stock ownership includes shares of common stock which are directly owned or owned by family members residing with the executive officer or <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-employee</div> director, or by family trusts, as well as vested options and vested restricted stock, and unvested restricted stock or equivalents, unless they are subject to achievement of performance targets, and common stock or stock equivalents credited to such executive officer or <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-employee</div> director under any deferred compensation plan, and (ii)&#160;common stock shall be valued per share using the <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">200-day</div> trailing average NYSE per share closing price. As of February&#160;1, 2025, each of our executive officers and <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-employee</div> directors was in compliance with our equity ownership policy (either because they owned adequate shares or are within the applicable grace period to obtain adequate shares). </div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">Insider Trading Policy </div></div></div></div><div style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Company&#8217;s <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:InsiderTrdPoliciesProcAdoptedFlag" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" format="ixt:fixed-true" id="ixv-10226">Insider Trading Policy</ix:nonNumeric>, which was filed as an exhibit to our most recent Annual Report filed with the SEC on March&#160;25, 2025 (the &#8220;Insider Trading Policy&#8221;), provides guidelines with respect to transactions in the Company&#8217;s securities and the handling of confidential information about the Company and the companies with which the Company does business. The purpose of the Insider Trading Policy is to promote compliance with federal, state and foreign securities laws that prohibit certain persons who are aware of material nonpublic information about a company from: (i)&#160;trading in securities of that company; or (ii)&#160;providing material </div><div style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="text-align:start; BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:12pt;width:100%;border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto">
<tr>
<td/>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:1%"/>
<td style="width:98%"/></tr>
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt">
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1pt; font-size: 12pt; font-family: ARIAL; line-height: normal;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;"><div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">14</div>&#8201;|&#8201;2025&#160;Proxy&#160;Statement</div></div></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap;text-align:right"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1pt; text-align: right; line-height: normal;">
<img alt="LOGO" src="g894376g85t00.jpg" style="width:0.740425in;height:0.149171in"/> </div></td></tr></table></div></div><div style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always"></div><hr style="color:#999999;height:3px;width:100%;clear:both"/><div style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold; margin-top: 1.67em; margin-bottom: 1.67em;"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></div><div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto"><div style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">nonpublic information to other persons who may trade on the basis of that information. The Insider Trading Policy applies to the Company&#8217;s executive officers, directors, and employees and other designated persons with access to the Company&#8217;s material nonpublic information, as well as to family members residing with them and any entities or family members whose transactions in the Company&#8217;s securities are directed by or subject to their influence and control. </div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">Pledging Policy </div></div></div></div><div style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">On March&#160;18, 2025, the Board adopted a pledging policy (the &#8220;Pledging Policy&#8221;). Under the Pledging Policy, executive officers and directors may pledge their Company securities (exclusive of options, warrants, restricted stock units or other rights to purchase Company securities) as collateral for a loan or an investment, provided that the maximum aggregate loan or investment amount collateralized by such pledged securities does not exceed fifty percent (50%) of the total value of the pledged securities (as measured at the time of the initial loan or investment). Providing these individuals flexibility in financial planning without having to rely on the sale of shares aligns their interests with those of our stockholders. </div><div style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="text-align:start; BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:12pt;width:100%;border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto">
<tr>
<td/>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:1%"/>
<td style="width:98%"/></tr>
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt">
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1pt; line-height: normal;">
<img alt="LOGO" src="g894376g85t00.jpg" style="width:0.740425in;height:0.149171in"/> </div></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap;text-align:right"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1pt; font-size: 12pt; font-family: ARIAL; text-align: right; line-height: normal;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">2025&#160;Proxy&#160;Statement&#8201;|&#8201;<div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">15</div></div></div></td></tr></table></div></div></div></div></div>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always"> </p>
<hr style="color:#999999;height:3px;width:100%;clear:both"/>
<h5 style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">In order to safeguard the integrity and effectiveness of the Pledging Policy, the following restrictions apply: </p> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">Each pledge is a &#8220;transaction&#8221; for purposes of the Insider Trading Policy and is subject to the <span style="white-space:nowrap">pre-clearance</span> and other restrictions set out in the Insider Trading Policy. No pledge can be initiated at any time when the pledgor is aware of any material nonpublic information about the Company. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">The pledgor must provide regular updates (at least quarterly) to the Company&#8217;s Compliance Officer (the &#8220;Compliance Officer&#8221;) regarding his or her pledged stock amount and loan amount. If necessary, the Compliance Officer will report to the Audit Committee any material change in the loan amount or pledged stock amount. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">The Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee will assess the risks to the Company of any pledge arrangement at least annually and at any such other time as is requested by the Compliance Officer. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">Subsequent declines in the value of the Company securities will not require the pledgor to provide additional collateral or reduce the amount of the loan or investment. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Anti-Hedging Policy </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Given that the aim of ownership of common stock is to ensure that employees and directors have a direct personal financial stake in our performance, hedging transactions on the part of employees and directors could be contrary to that purpose. Therefore, we have adopted an anti-hedging policy which states that the implementation by an employee or director of hedging strategies or transactions using short sales, puts, calls or other types of financial instruments (including, but not limited to, prepaid variable forward contracts, equity swaps, collars, and exchange funds) based upon the value of our common stock and applied to equity securities granted to such employee or director, or held, directly or indirectly, by such employee or director, is strictly prohibited. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Corporate Governance Guidelines; Certifications </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Board has adopted Corporate Governance Guidelines. The Corporate Governance Guidelines are available on our website at <span style="font-style:italic"><span style="font-family:ARIAL;color:#1e3aff"><span style="text-decoration:underline">http://investor.gamestop.com/corporate-governance</span></span> </span>and are available in print to any stockholder who requests them in writing to our Secretary, GameStop Corp., 625 Westport Parkway, Grapevine, Texas 76051. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">On an annual basis, our General Counsel submits to the NYSE the annual certification required by Section&#160;303A.12(a) of the NYSE Listed Company Manual. In addition, we have filed with the SEC as exhibits to our Annual Report the certifications of our Chief Executive Officer and Principal Financial Officer required pursuant to Section&#160;302 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act relating to the quality of our public disclosure. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Communications Between Stockholders and Interested Parties and the Board </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Stockholders and other interested persons seeking to communicate with the Board should submit any communications in writing to our Secretary, GameStop Corp., 625 Westport Parkway, Grapevine, Texas 76051. Any such communication must be accompanied by the following information: (i)&#160;if the person submitting the communication is a stockholder, state the number of shares beneficially owned by the stockholder making the communication, and (ii)&#160;if the person submitting the communication is not a stockholder and is submitting the communication as an interested party, the nature of the person&#8217;s interest in the Company. Our Secretary will forward such communication to the full Board or to any individual director or directors (including the presiding director of the executive sessions of the <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-management</span> directors or the <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-management</span> directors as a group) to whom the communication is directed. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Attendance at Annual Meetings </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">All members of the Board are expected to attend the annual meeting and be available to address questions or concerns raised by stockholders. At our 2024 annual meeting of stockholders, all of our then incumbent directors who stood for <span style="white-space:nowrap">re-election</span> at the 2024 annual meeting attended the meeting virtually. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Succession Planning </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Board is responsible for succession planning and succession planning issues are discussed as a matter of course at regular Board meetings. In addition, the Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee periodically reviews succession plans for our senior executive officer positions, including the Chief Executive Officer. </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap"> <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold"><span style="color:#e2231a">16</span>&#8201;|&#8201;2025&#160;Proxy&#160;Statement</p></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>

<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always"> </p>
<hr style="color:#999999;height:3px;width:100%;clear:both"/>
<h5 style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Risk Oversight </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Responsibility for risk oversight resides with the full Board. Committees help the Board carry out this responsibility by focusing on key areas of risk inherent in the business. The Audit Committee oversees risk associated with financial and accounting matters, including compliance with legal and regulatory requirements, related-party transactions and our financial reporting and internal control systems. The Audit Committee also oversees our internal audit function and regularly meets separately with representatives of our internal audit team, the Principal Financial Officer, external auditors and other financial and executive management. The Compensation Committee oversees risks associated with compensation policies and the retention and development of executive talent, including the development of policies that do not encourage excessive risk-taking by our executives. These policies include various factors to help mitigate risk, including vesting periods, equity ownership policies, and clawback provisions. The Compensation Committee and management also regularly review our compensation policies to determine effectiveness and to assess the risk they present to us. Based on this review, we have concluded that our compensation policies and procedures are not reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on us. In addition, at least annually, the Board conducts a formal business review including a risk assessment related to our existing business and new initiatives. Because overseeing risk is an ongoing process and inherent in strategic decisions, the Board also discusses risk throughout the year at other meetings in relation to specific topics or actions. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_10">Director Compensation </p> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Historically, each <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</span> director (other than Mr.&#160;Cohen) elected at the annual meeting received a restricted stock unit (&#8220;RSU&#8221;) award with respect to a number of shares determined by dividing $200,000 by the average closing price of our common stock for the 30 trading days immediately preceding the annual meeting. Such RSUs vested upon the earlier of the next regularly scheduled annual meeting following the award date or the grantee&#8217;s death. One share of common stock was distributed in respect of each vested RSU within 60 days following the relevant vesting date or event. Under this structure, no cash compensation was paid to our <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</span> directors. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Commencing with the 2024 annual meeting, the Board eliminated all compensation for <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</span> directors. The Board believes that this new policy is consistent with the Company&#8217;s philosophy of creating an ownership mentality, encouraging investment by directors in the Company, and aligning the interests of our directors with our stockholders. Under the current policy, our directors are only compensated to the extent their own investment in the Company appreciates, uniquely situating our directors to drive stockholder value. The Board&#8217;s equity ownership policy described above remains in full force and effect. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Mr.&#160;Cohen declined to receive any compensation for his service as a director in fiscal 2024. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The following table provides information regarding compensation of our current <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</span> directors for fiscal 2024. </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Mr.&#160;Turner was appointed to the Board on November&#160;18, 2024. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We have reimbursed and will continue to reimburse our directors for reasonable expenses incurred in connection with their attendance at Board and committee meetings. Because the Board believes that it is important for each director to have a financial stake in the Company to help align the director&#8217;s interests with those of our stockholders, we require our directors to maintain a certain level of ownership of common stock. For a description of the equity ownership policy, see &#8220;Corporate Governance-Equity Ownership Policy&#8221; above. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Directors who are also executive officers (presently, Mr.&#160;Cohen) do not receive additional compensation for their services as directors, and none of the directors receive additional compensation for their services as committee chairpersons, Lead Independent Director or as our Chair of the Board. Please see the portions of this proxy statement regarding executive compensation for a description of Mr.&#160;Cohen&#8217;s compensation. </p>

<td style="width:2%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(2)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">On April&#160;4, 2024, Mr.&#160;Patel departed from service as our Chief Operating Officer. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Business Experience of Executive Officers </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify"><span style="font-weight:bold">Ryan Cohen. </span>For background information on Mr.&#160;Cohen, please see &#8220;Biographies of Director Nominees.&#8221; </p> <p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify"><span style="font-weight:bold">Dan Moore. </span>Mr.&#160;Moore serves as the Company&#8217;s Principal Financial Officer, a role he has had since March 2024, and as the Company&#8217;s Principal Accounting Officer, a role he has had since August 2023. Prior to being appointed Principal Financial and Accounting Officer, Mr.&#160;Moore served in the following roles since joining the Company in July 2021: interim Principal Financial Officer (August 2023 to March 2024); Vice President, Corporate Global Controller (September 2022 to August 2023); and Vice President, Global Tax (July 2021 to September 2022). Prior to joining the Company in 2021, Mr.&#160;Moore served as Vice President, Tax at Elevate Textiles and Director of International Tax at Roper Technologies. Overall, Mr.&#160;Moore has more than 19 years&#8217; experience in finance, accounting and tax. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify"><span style="font-weight:bold">Mark Robinson</span>. Mr.&#160;Robinson serves as our General Counsel and Secretary, a role he has had since January 2022. Since joining the Company in August 2015, Mr.&#160;Robinson has served in the following roles: General Manager (June 2023 to September 2023); Vice President, Assistant General Counsel (June 2020 to January 2022); and Senior Counsel (August 2015 to June 2020). In his current role, he oversees the legal and human resources functions of the Company. Prior to joining the Company in 2015, Mr.&#160;Robinson held positions as an attorney at law firms Norton Rose Fulbright and Jones Day, where he provided counsel on corporate and finance transactions. </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_12">Security Ownership of Certain Beneficial Owners and Management and Related Stockholder Matters </p> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The following table sets forth the number of shares of our common stock beneficially owned on April&#160;21, 2025 by each director, each of the NEOs, each holder of 5% or more of our common stock and all of our directors and executive officers as a group (including shares of common stock that such person or holder has the right to acquire within 60 days of April&#160;21, 2025). Except as otherwise noted, the individual director or executive officer (including the former executive officer who was a NEO) or his or her immediate family members had sole voting and investment power with respect to the identified securities. Except as otherwise noted, the address of each person listed below is c/o GameStop Corp., 625 Westport Parkway, Grapevine, Texas 76051. The total number of shares of our common stock outstanding as of April&#160;21, 2025 was 447,300,514. </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="width:2%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(10)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Of these shares, 25,788 are unvested restricted stock units. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_13">Compensation Committee Interlocks and Insider Participation </p> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The members of the Compensation Committee are Alan Attal (Chair), Larry Cheng and Jim Grube, none of whom has ever been an employee of the Company. No member of the Compensation Committee had a relationship requiring disclosure in this Proxy Statement under Items 404 or 407 of SEC Regulation <span style="white-space:nowrap">S-K.</span> </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>

<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:16pt;width:100%;border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto">


<tr>

<td/>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:1%"/>
<td style="width:98%"/></tr>


<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:16pt">
<td style="vertical-align:top;white-space:nowrap" id="toc894376_14"><span style="font-weight:bold">PROPOSAL&#8201;2:</span></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.63em; font-size:16pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">ADVISORY VOTE ON EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION</span></span></p></td></tr>
</table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We believe that it is appropriate to solicit the views of our stockholders regarding the compensation of our NEOs. Accordingly, and in accordance with SEC rules implemented under Section&#160;14A of the Exchange Act, the Company seeks a <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-binding</span> advisory vote from our stockholders on the compensation of our NEOs as described in this Proxy Statement. Although the advisory vote on Proposal 2 is <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-binding,</span> as provided by law, the Compensation Committee of the Board and the Board will review the results of the vote and, consistent with our record of stockholder engagement, will consider the results of the vote when making future compensation decisions. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">As discussed more fully in the &#8220;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#8221; in this Proxy Statement, the Compensation Committee believes the NEOs should be compensated commensurate with their success in maintaining a high level of performance necessary for the Company to produce ongoing and sustained value for our stockholders. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Following our 2023 annual meeting&#8217;s advisory vote on the frequency of the advisory vote on executive compensation, we conduct an advisory vote on executive compensation on an annual basis. This is an advisory vote and is not binding upon the Company, the Compensation Committee or the Board. Therefore, stockholders are not ultimately voting for the approval or disapproval of the Board&#8217;s recommendation on this proposal. The result of the vote will not impact any compensation that has already been paid or awarded to the executive officers. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Except for costs to the Company of providing Ryan Cohen, our President, Chief Executive Officer and Chairman, executive security services in accordance with the independently-assessed executive security program established by our Board, Mr.&#160;Cohen, has declined all forms of salary, benefits and other compensation from the Company. Therefore, Mr.&#160;Cohen primarily only benefits to the extent his existing investment in the Company appreciates and is therefore uniquely situated to drive stockholder value. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The compensation for our other executive officers is designed to ensure that such officers are also incentivized to drive long-term stockholder value. We accomplished this goal through a model that purposefully prioritizes equity incentives that are both time- and performance-based. We strongly encourage stockholders to read the &#8220;Compensation Discussion and Analysis,&#8221; the compensation tables and the accompanying narrative disclosures in this Proxy Statement which discuss in greater detail the compensation of our executive officers, the Company&#8217;s compensation philosophy and the factors that the Compensation Committee considered in making compensation decisions. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Accordingly, the Board recommends that stockholders vote FOR the following resolution: </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">&#8220;RESOLVED, that the Company&#8217;s stockholders approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation of the NEOs, as disclosed in the Company&#8217;s Proxy Statement for the 2025 annual meeting of stockholders pursuant to the compensation disclosure rules of the SEC, including the Compensation Discussion and Analysis, the Summary Compensation Table (&#8220;SCT&#8221;) and the other related tables and disclosure.&#8221; </p> <p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold;text-align:justify">THE BOARD UNANIMOUSLY RECOMMENDS THAT STOCKHOLDERS VOTE <span style="text-decoration:underline">FOR</span> THE APPROVAL, ON A <span style="white-space:nowrap">NON-BINDING</span> ADVISORY BASIS, OF THE RESOLUTION ON COMPENSATION OF OUR NAMED EXECUTIVE OFFICERS. PROXIES SOLICITED BY THIS PROXY STATEMENT WILL BE VOTED <span style="text-decoration:underline">FOR</span> THIS PROPOSAL UNLESS A VOTE AGAINST THE PROPOSAL OR AN ABSTENTION IS SPECIFICALLY INDICATED. </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

<hr style="color:#999999;height:3px;width:100%;clear:both"/>
<h5 style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_15">Compensation Discussion and Analysis </p> <p style="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_16"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Compensation Philosophy </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We believe it is mutually beneficial for the Company and our employees to instill an ownership mentality and have a significant majority of compensation in the form of equity. Accordingly, our compensation program is designed to drive ownership of our work, our capital and our relationship to the customer as we focus on profitability. Our executive compensation program is administered by the Compensation Committee. The program is based upon the following guiding principles: </p> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">The primary compensation opportunities we offer should align the long-term interests of our employees with those of our stockholders, encourage long-term strategic thinking, and motivate and reward executives for achieving <span style="white-space:nowrap">go-forward</span> business strategies and maximizing stockholder value. Therefore, a substantial portion of management&#8217;s compensation will be in the form of long-term equity compensation. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">To retain and motivate talent, in limited circumstances, we offer short-term equity incentive compensation. These short-term equity incentives focus on aligning employees&#8217; compensation with annual, objective financial goals. Accordingly, management may be entitled to short-term equity compensation if specified annual, objective financial goals are achieved by the Company. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Compensation Committee believes our compensation model is reflective of these guiding principles. The vast majority of our executive compensation program, which is mainly comprised of long-term equity incentives, is tied to our stock price, directly aligning the interests of our executives with those of our stockholders. To the extent the Company succeeds in achieving our business strategy, our executives will be rewarded through stock price appreciation; however, failure to achieve our strategy and deliver sustainable stockholder value creation will lead to an erosion of realized pay to our executives. In limited circumstances, we also use short-term equity incentives based on the achievement of objective financial goals. This fundamental commitment to pay for performance underscores our compensation decision-making. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">As mentioned above, in accordance with the independently-assessed executive security program established by our Board, the Company provides Mr.&#160;Cohen, our President, Chief Executive Officer and Chairman, with executive security services. We believe these services and costs are reasonable, appropriate, necessary and in the best interests of the Company and its stockholders, as they enable Mr.&#160;Cohen to carry out his responsibilities and, therefore, mitigate risks to our business. While we do not consider these security services to be a personal benefit for, or compensation paid to, Mr.&#160;Cohen because they arise from, and are necessary for the carrying out of, his employment responsibilities, the aggregate incremental costs to the Company of providing these services for fiscal year 2024 is set forth in the &#8220;All Other Compensation&#8221; column in the SCT below. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Mr.&#160;Cohen has declined all other forms of salary, benefits and other compensation. Mr.&#160;Cohen therefore primarily only benefits to the extent his existing investment in the stock of the Company appreciates, which directly aligns his interest with that of our stockholders. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The key elements of our compensation program for NEOs (excluding Mr.&#160;Cohen) are: base salary, new hire bonuses and equity incentives, as described below. </p> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify"><span style="font-style:italic">Base Salary</span>. The base salaries of our NEOs are purposely designed to provide a modest level of cash compensation that is significantly less than those paid to senior leadership at similarly positioned companies, and significantly less than base salaries historically paid to our former executive officers. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify"><span style="font-style:italic">New Hire Bonuses</span>. NEOs receive a cash bonus typically paid during their first two years of employment to maintain targeted compensation near-term while their equity vesting schedule ramps up over time. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify"><span style="font-style:italic">Long-Term Equity Incentives</span>. The primary component of a NEO&#8217;s total compensation is equity compensation issued in the form of time-vested restricted stock units. Accordingly, NEOs receive sizable stock-based awards at the time of hire and are also eligible for stock-based awards on a periodic basis. Because our compensation program is designed to reward long-term performance and operate over a period of years, NEOs typically receive stock-based awards that vest over a number of years. Annual total compensation as reported in the SCT below includes the entire fair value as of the grant date of a stock award granted in that year, without regard to the fact that the grant vests over a number of years. As a result, our NEO&#8217;s total compensation as reported will be higher in years in which they receive a grant compared to years in which they do not receive a grant. While the long-term equity incentives do not vest based on performance targets, due to the structure of our compensation plan, executive interests are directly linked with long-term stockholder performance. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify"><span style="font-style:italic">Short-Term Equity Incentives</span>. To retain and motivate management to drive performance over annual periods, in limited circumstances, the Company offers short-term equity incentive compensation based on the achievement of objective </p></td></tr></table>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:12pt;width:100%;border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto">

<tr>

<td/>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:1%"/>
<td style="width:98%"/></tr>
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt">
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap"> <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold"><span style="color:#e2231a">22</span>&#8201;|&#8201;2025&#160;Proxy&#160;Statement</p></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap;text-align:right"> <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:1pt;text-align:right">


<img src="g894376g85t00.jpg" alt="LOGO" style="width:0.740425in;height:0.149171in"/>
</p></td></tr></table>

</div></div>

<h5 style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">

<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:8%">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">
financial goals. These annual, objective financial goals are selected in order to motivate our executives to focus on achievement of our key short-term financial criteria, specifically emphasizing profitability. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify"><span style="font-style:italic">Limited Perquisites. </span>We believe that our executives should be compensated primarily through equity incentives and base salary. Other than Mr.&#160;Cohen&#8217;s executive security, we have not established, nor do we have any intention of establishing, any perquisites. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify"><span style="font-style:italic">Limited Severance Benefits</span>. All of our NEOs are employed on an <span style="white-space:nowrap">at-will</span> basis. We no longer offer employment agreements and provide severance benefits only in very limited circumstances. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Compensation Committee oversees risks associated with our compensation policies and the retention and development of executive talent, including the development of policies that do not encourage excessive risk-taking by our executives. These policies include various factors to help mitigate risk, including vesting periods, investment policies, equity ownership policies and clawback provisions. The Compensation Committee and management also regularly review our compensation policies to determine effectiveness and to assess the risk they present to the Company. Based on this review, we have concluded that our compensation policies and procedures are not reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on the Company. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Changes in Senior Management </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">On March&#160;25, 2024, the Board promoted Mr.&#160;Moore, who had previously been interim Principal Financial Officer, to the role of Principal Financial Officer. Mr.&#160;Moore continues to serve in his role as the Principal Accounting Officer of the Company. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">On April&#160;4, 2024, Mr.&#160;Patel departed from service as our Chief Operating Officer. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Named Executive Officers </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">This Compensation Discussion and Analysis covers the fiscal 2024 compensation for the following NEOs, as determined under SEC rules (titles below reflect executives&#8217; current roles): </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;width:100%;border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto">


<tr>

<td style="width:31%"/>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:1%"/>
<td style="width:68%"/></tr>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;vertical-align:bottom"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:9pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:bold"><span style="color:#ffffff">Title</span></span></span></p></td></tr>


<tr style="font-size:1pt">
<td style="height:0.75pt;background-color:#000000"/>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:13pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL">Former Chief Operating Officer</p></td></tr>
</table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_17"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Response to Advisory Vote on Executive Compensation </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">A substantial portion of our stockholders (98.6% of votes cast) approved the fiscal 2023 compensation for our NEOs at the 2024 annual meeting of stockholders. We interpreted these results as a validation of our executive compensation program. We believe our current approach ensures that the long-term interests of our employees are aligned with those of our stockholders. The Compensation Committee will continue to consider alternatives based on feedback from its stockholders and revise the executive compensation program as it deems appropriate. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_18"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Compensation Determination Process </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Compensation Committee is responsible for developing the compensation levels for our NEOs. In determining the compensation levels for new NEOs, the Compensation Committee considered a variety of factors, including the NEOs&#8217; level of responsibility and expected contributions to our future success. The Compensation Committee may also periodically modify the compensation levels or grant additional equity to existing NEOs and other employees based on the factors set out above as well as past contributions to our performance. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_19"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Key Elements of Compensation </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Our policies with respect to each of the key elements of NEO compensation are discussed below. In addition, while the elements of compensation described below are considered separately, the Compensation Committee also considers and reviews the full compensation package we provide to our executive officers. See below for details on our 2024 compensation program. Except for </p>

<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Effective as of April&#160;4, 2024, Mr.&#160;Moore&#8217;s annual base salary was increased to $200,000 in connection with his promotion to Principal Financial and Accounting Officer. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">New Hire Bonuses </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Following their hire date or promotion date, as applicable, NEOs receive a <span style="white-space:nowrap">one-time</span> cash bonus that pays out over time and is intended to maintain targeted total compensation near-term while their equity vesting schedule ramps up over time. These bonuses are paid in <span style="white-space:nowrap">bi-weekly</span> installments beginning on the hire date or adoption date of the new compensation structure and typically decrease over time. While most new hire bonuses span the first two years from hire or adoption of the compensation program, they can bridge into subsequent years to address various pay factors as outlined in the Compensation Determination Process section. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">In connection with his promotion to Principal Financial and Accounting Officer, on April&#160;4, 2024, Mr.&#160;Moore&#8217;s total targeted compensation was increased and, on July&#160;1, 2024, Mr.&#160;Moore was granted a restricted stock unit award, as described below. In order to maintain Mr.&#160;Moore&#8217;s target total compensation near-term while his new equity vesting schedule ramped up over time, Mr.&#160;Moore was awarded a cash bonus of $28,877, which was similar in form to a <span style="white-space:nowrap">&#8220;new-hire&#8221;</span> bonus. This bonus is reflected below in the 2023-2024 period. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Mr.&#160;Cohen has declined all forms of cash bonuses. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">New hire bonuses offered to the NEOs are below: </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

Mr.&#160;Robinson received a grant in recognition of his contributions to the Company. The service requirements otherwise applicable to these awards may be waived in certain scenarios; see &#8220;Offer Letters and Severance/Change in Control Benefits&#8221; elsewhere in this Proxy Statement. </p>

<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The target value at vesting is indicative of the applicable NEOs long-term equity compensation from the anniversary of such NEO&#8217;s hire date occurring in the first year noted to the anniversary of such hire date in each subsequent year noted. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Short-Term Equity Incentives </p> <p style="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">On September&#160;5, 2024, the Compensation Committee approved performance awards pursuant to the GameStop Corp. 2022 Incentive Plan (the &#8220;2022 Plan&#8221;) for Mr.&#160;Robinson and Mr.&#160;Moore for fiscal years 2024 and 2025 (&#8220;STI&#8221;). Such performance awards (i)&#160;will consist of restricted stock, (ii)&#160;have intended grant values equal to $500,000 for each fiscal year, (iii)&#160;are subject to vesting based on the achievement of $50&#160;million in operating profit (excluding royalties) for the Company&#8217;s United States geographic segment for each such fiscal year and each officer&#8217;s continued employment, and (iv)&#160;will be granted, to the extent such performance criteria is satisfied for the applicable fiscal year, on April&#160;1 of the following year, and will vest in equal quarterly parts on the grant date and the following July&#160;1, October&#160;1 and January 1. The performance criteria was not achieved for fiscal year 2024 and, therefore, no portion of the STI awards were paid on April&#160;1, 2025. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Mr.&#160;Cohen has declined all forms of short-term equity compensation. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Target Total Compensation Summary </p> <p style="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">In summary of the compensation elements detailed above, target total compensation for NEOs under our compensation program for the next four years is described in the table below. We analyze target compensation for each NEO on an annual basis from hire date. </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="width:2%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(1)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The target value at vesting is indicative of the applicable NEOs long-term equity compensation from the anniversary of such NEO&#8217;s hire date occurring in the first year noted to the anniversary of such hire date in each subsequent year noted. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">As described above, the Compensation Committee considers the following when determining total compensation for NEOs (other than Mr.&#160;Cohen): </p> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify"><span style="font-weight:bold">Reward Executives Who Believe in the Company to Achieve <span style="white-space:nowrap">Go-Forward</span> Business Strategy</span>: By awarding <span style="white-space:nowrap">one-time,</span> new hire RSU grants, our executive team has the potential for significant rewards through this program, but only to the extent the team executes on our long-range business and strategic objectives that result in share price appreciation. Any decrease in stock price will erode the realizable value that could be earned by our executives upon vesting. The structure of this Long-Term Incentive program ensures that we attract and retain executives who are willing to tie the vast majority of their compensation to stockholder value creation, given their belief in our long-term business strategy. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify"><span style="font-weight:bold">Retain and Motivate Executives Who Believe in the Company</span>: Periodically providing our executive team with short-term equity incentives encourages achievement of specific <span style="white-space:nowrap">one-year</span> financial and management goals. These short-term equity incentives also align executives&#8217; compensation with the Company&#8217;s financial performance and strategic initiatives. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">As mentioned above, except for the incremental costs to the Company of providing Mr.&#160;Cohen executive security services in accordance with the independently-assessed executive security program established by our Board, Mr.&#160;Cohen has declined all forms of salary, benefits and other compensation from the Company for serving as President, Chief Executive Officer and Chairman. Mr.&#160;Cohen therefore primarily only benefits to the extent his existing investment in the stock of the Company appreciates, which directly aligns his interest with that of our stockholders. </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

<hr style="color:#999999;height:3px;width:100%;clear:both"/>
<h5 style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_20"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Offer Letters and Severance/Change in Control Benefits </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We have issued offer letters or continuing employment letters to the NEOs (other than Mr.&#160;Cohen) detailing the terms of each NEO&#8217;s employment (the &#8220;Offer Letters&#8221;). The employment of all of our NEOs is &#8220;at will&#8221; and may be terminated by the Company or the executive at any time, and each executive is restricted from competing with us for a period of time after termination of employment regardless of the reason for the termination. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Under the terms of the Offer Letters, each executive is entitled to all benefits afforded to management personnel or as determined by the Board, including, but not limited to, insurance programs, vacation, sick leave and 401(k) benefits. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Mr.&#160;Robinson&#8217;s Offer Letter also provides that, upon his termination of employment without cause, Mr.&#160;Robinson, subject to an effective release, would receive (A)&#160;six months of base pay, (B)&#160;an amount equal to six months of COBRA premiums for him and his dependents, (C)&#160;any transformation bonus installments that had not yet been paid, (D)&#160;the portion of any equity award that was scheduled to be paid during the <span style="white-space:nowrap">six-month</span> period following termination, and (E)&#160;any long-term incentive cash that was otherwise scheduled to vest during the <span style="white-space:nowrap">six-month</span> period following termination. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Offer Letter of Mr.&#160;Patel provided that upon his termination of employment without cause, Mr.&#160;Patel, subject to an effective release, would receive (A)&#160;six months of base pay, (B)&#160;an amount equal to six months of COBRA premiums for the executive and his dependents, (C)&#160;any new hire bonus installments which have not already been paid, and (D)&#160;the portion of the executive&#8217;s equity awards that would otherwise vest during the six months immediately following their termination. On April&#160;4, 2024, the Company and Mr.&#160;Patel entered into a Separation Agreement and Mutual Release of Claims, which was filed with the SEC on April&#160;4, 2024 (the &#8220;Separation Agreement&#8221;). The Separation Agreement provided for Mr.&#160;Patel&#8217;s departure from the Company as the Company&#8217;s Chief Operating Officer, effective April&#160;4, 2024. The Separation Agreement contains a customary general release of claims by Mr.&#160;Patel and the Company and provides for the following: (A)&#160;a lump sum payment to Mr.&#160;Patel consisting of (i)&#160;ten weeks of base salary, (ii)&#160;an amount equal to the applicable premiums for COBRA continuation coverage for two months, and (iii)&#160;thirty percent of the remaining unearned portion of Mr.&#160;Patel&#8217;s <span style="white-space:nowrap">sign-on</span> bonus, and (B)&#160;acceleration of vesting of thirty percent of the portion of Mr.&#160;Patel&#8217;s equity awards that were otherwise scheduled to vest in the ordinary course during the <span style="white-space:nowrap">six-month</span> period immediately following his separation date. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The triggering events which would result in the payment of the severance amounts described above were selected because they provide the applicable employees with a guaranteed level of financial protection upon loss of employment and are considered competitive with severance provisions being offered currently in the market. The estimated payments upon a hypothetical termination for each of the NEOs as of the end of fiscal 2024 are detailed in &#8220;Offer Letters and Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control&#8221; below. In addition, the actual payments made to Mr.&#160;Patel are shown below under the heading &#8220;Actual Executive Separations.&#8221; </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_21"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Other Compensation Considerations </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Clawback of Awards </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We have adopted a formal clawback policy to recover past compensation awards from executive officers in the event of fraud or a restatement. For a description of the clawback policy, see &#8220;Corporate Governance&#8212;Clawback Policy&#8221; above. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Stock Ownership </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We have adopted a stock ownership policy which requires our NEOs and <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</span> directors to be stockholders. The Compensation Committee believes that ownership of stock of the Company that is material to the income of the individuals involved provides an appropriate incentive to such officers and <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</span> directors and aligns their interests with the interests of our stockholders. For a description of the stock ownership policy, see &#8220;Corporate Governance&#8212;Equity Ownership Policy&#8221; above. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Insider Trading Policy </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Company&#8217;s Insider Trading Policy promotes compliance with federal, state and foreign securities laws that prohibit certain persons who are aware of material nonpublic information about a company from: (i)&#160;trading in securities of that company; or (ii)&#160;providing material nonpublic information to other persons who may trade on the basis of that information. For a description of the Company&#8217;s Insider Trading Policy, see &#8220;Corporate Governance&#8212;Equity Ownership Policy&#8221; above. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Pledging Policy </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Company adopted a pledging policy to provide its directors and executive officers flexibility in financial planning without having to sell their shares of the Company, aligning their interests with those of our stockholders. For a description of the pledging policy, see &#8220;Corporate Governance&#8212;Equity Ownership Policy&#8221; above. </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>
