<h5 style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Anti-Hedging </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We have adopted a formal anti-hedging policy prohibiting our employees and <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</span> directors from entering into any form of hedging strategies or transactions using short sales, puts, calls or other types of financial instruments to protect against a loss in value of our common stock. For a description of the anti-hedging policy, see &#8220;Corporate Governance&#8212;Anti-Hedging Policy&#8221; above. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Retirement Benefits </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Each of our executive officers is entitled to participate in our defined contribution 401(k) plan on the same basis as all other eligible employees. Historically, we matched the contributions of participants, subject to certain criteria. Effective January&#160;1, 2024, the Company suspended employer matching contributions for all employees. Under the terms of the 2024 401(k) plan, as prescribed by the IRS, the contribution of any participating employee is limited to a maximum percentage of annual pay or a maximum dollar amount ($23,000 <span style="white-space:nowrap">pre-tax</span> and $7,500 <span style="white-space:nowrap">catch-up</span> for 2024). Our executive officers are subject to these limitations and therefore we do not consider our retirement benefits to be a material portion of the compensation program for our executive officers. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Life Insurance </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Historically, all of our active NEOs participated in our standard salaried employee group term life insurance program, but have their death benefits under that program increased to three times the employee&#8217;s base salary, up to a maximum death benefit of $1,500,000. The Company&#8217;s paid life-insurance program was discontinued on January&#160;1, 2024. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Benefits and Perquisites </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We maintain traditional health and welfare benefit plans, which are generally offered to all employees (subject to basic plan eligibility requirements) and are consistent with the types of benefits offered by other similar corporations. We believe in a consistent benefit experience for all employees across the organization, regardless of level. As a result, we have eliminated and no longer offer certain executive-level perquisites sometimes offered by similar corporations, including disability insurance commensurate with executive salaries, third-party financial planning services, reimbursement of certain otherwise uninsured medical expenses and annual physical examinations. As discussed above, the Company does provide Mr.&#160;Cohen with executive security services. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_22">Compensation Committee Report on Executive Compensation </p> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Compensation Committee has reviewed and discussed the Compensation Discussion and Analysis contained in this Proxy Statement with members of our management. Based on such review and discussions and relying thereon, we have recommended to the Board that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis set forth above be included in our 2024 Annual Report on Form <span style="white-space:nowrap">10-K</span> and in this Proxy Statement. </p> <p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Compensation Committee </p> <p style="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Alan Attal, Chair </p> <p style="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Larry Cheng </p> <p style="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Jim Grube </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:1%"/>
<td style="width:98%"/></tr>

<hr style="color:#999999;height:3px;width:100%;clear:both"/>
<h5 style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_23">Executive Compensation Tables </p> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_24"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Summary Compensation Table </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The following table sets forth the compensation earned by our NEOs during the fiscal years indicated. Effective as of April&#160;4, 2024, Mr.&#160;Moore&#8217;s salary increased from $170,000 to $200,000 in connection with his promotion to Principal Financial and Accounting Officer. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

The bonus amount in 2024 for Mr.&#160;Moore was issued in connection with Mr.&#160;Moore&#8217;s promotion to Principal Financial Officer and was issued in order to maintain Mr.&#160;Moore&#8217;s target total compensation near-term while his new equity vesting schedule ramped up over time. The bonus amount in 2023 for Mr.&#160;Robinson was composed of a $76,154 bonus attributed to his adoption of the new compensation program beginning in July 2021. Bonus amounts for Mr.&#160;Patel are composed of new hire bonuses as detailed in his offer letter. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

The amount reported in the &#8220;All Other Compensation&#8221; column in fiscal 2024 for Mr.&#160;Patel represents cash severance payments.  <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_25"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Grants of Plan-Based Awards in Fiscal 2024 </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The following table shows all grants of plan-based awards, which consisted of grants of time-vested restricted stock units made in fiscal 2024. </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;width:100%;border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto">

<td style="padding-bottom:4pt ;vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:0.38em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><span style="color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:bold"><span style="color:#ffffff">Name</span></span></span></p></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom"/>

 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_26"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Outstanding Equity Awards at Fiscal 2024 <span style="white-space:nowrap">Year-End</span> </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The following table provides information for the NEOs regarding outstanding equity awards held as of February&#160;1, 2025. In accordance with SEC rules, the <span style="white-space:nowrap">year-end</span> values in the table for the market value of shares that have not vested have been calculated based on the $26.90 per share closing price of common stock on January&#160;31, 2025 (the last trading date of the fiscal year). </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_28"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Offer Letters and Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We have issued offer letters or continuing employment letters to our NEOs (other than Mr.&#160;Cohen) detailing the terms of each NEO&#8217;s employment. See &#8220;Offer Letters and Severance/Change in Control Benefits&#8221; above for a description of the terms of these offer letters. Hypothetical estimates of the amounts that would be owed to the NEOs upon termination of their employment or upon a change in control are presented in the table directly below. In accordance with rules of the SEC, the hypothetical estimates have been computed on the assumption that the termination or change of control occurred on February&#160;1, 2025, the last day of our most recently completed fiscal year. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The employment of Mr.&#160;Patel terminated prior to February&#160;1, 2025 and we have therefore excluded him from the table below. We have described below under the heading &#8220;Actual Executive Separations&#8221; the actual amounts received by Mr.&#160;Patel upon cessation of his employment. </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Actual Executive Separations </p> <p style="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Mr.&#160;Patel ceased employment with the Company on April&#160;4, 2024, and was entitled to the severance payments and benefits provided for in the Separation Agreement. The actual amounts received by Mr.&#160;Patel are summarized below. Stock values indicated below were calculated based on the closing price of our common stock at the time of vesting. Mr.&#160;Patel executed a general release of claims against the Company and its affiliates as a condition of receiving these payments and benefits. </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:2%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(4)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The amount shown in the table represents the value of 94,648 shares of time-vested restricted stock that vested on an accelerated basis in accordance with the terms of the Separation Agreement, based on the closing price of our common stock on April&#160;18, 2024. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_29">CEO Pay Ratio </p> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">As required by the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act of 2010, we are disclosing the ratio of the total annual compensation of our Chief Executive Officer to that of our median employee. We identified the median employee among all our employees as of February&#160;1, 2025 (the &#8220;determination date&#8221;). </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We are a global retail company with approximately 6,500 full-time salaried and hourly employees and between 11,000 and 17,000 part-time hourly employees worldwide, depending on the time of year. As discussed above, Mr.&#160;Cohen has declined all forms of compensation, except for the incremental costs to the Company of providing Mr.&#160;Cohen executive security services in accordance with the independently-assessed executive security program established by our Board. Therefore, his total annualized compensation as of the determination date was $268,553. For fiscal 2024, our median employee is a part-time hourly employee in one of our U.S. stores who worked an average of 22 hours per week. The annual compensation of the median employee was $14,726.85 for fiscal 2024. Based on this information, the ratio of the fiscal 2024 annual total compensation of our Chief Executive Officer to that of our median employee was approximately 18 to 1. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">In order to identify the median employee in terms of compensation across our global population of employees, we utilized total annual earnings from the 2024 calendar year, which include, but are not limited to, salary/hourly wages, overtime, bonus and commissions. We used <span style="white-space:nowrap">W-2</span> earnings for the U.S. employee population and the <span style="white-space:nowrap">W-2</span> equivalent earnings for the international employee population. We annualized the compensation for permanent associates who joined the Company after January&#160;1, 2024. Full-time equivalency adjustments were not performed for part-time associates. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We believe our CEO pay ratio is a reasonable estimate calculated in a manner consistent with the SEC pay ratio rules and methods for disclosure. The SEC rules do not specify a single methodology in identifying the median employee and in calculating that person&#8217;s annual compensation. Accordingly, the pay ratio reported by other companies may not be comparable to the Company&#8217;s pay ratio disclosed above. </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

For fiscal 2021, our PEOs included both <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:PeoName" contextRef="P01_31_2021To01_29_2022_MatthewFurlongMemberecdIndividualAxis" id="ixv-10305">Matthew Furlong</ix:nonNumeric> and former CEO <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:PeoName" contextRef="P01_31_2021To01_29_2022_GeorgeEShermanMemberecdIndividualAxis" id="ixv-10306">George E. Sherman</ix:nonNumeric>. </div></td></tr></table><div style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="text-align:start; BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:2%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(2)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; font-size: 8pt; font-family: ARIAL; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;">In calculating the &#8220;Compensation Actually Paid&#8221; or &#8220;CAP&#8221; amounts reflected in these columns, the fair value or change in fair value, as applicable, of the equity award adjustments included in such calculations were computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718. Time-vested restricted stock/unit grant date fair values are calculated using the closing stock price as of date of grant. Adjustments have been made using the stock price as of fiscal <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">year-end</div> and as of each date of vest. Performance-vested restricted stock fair values are valued at zero at each respective measurement date, given all outstanding performance-vested restricted stock were accrued at and estimated to be earned below threshold (i.e., all shares forfeited) as of each respective measurement date. The assumptions used to calculate the fair value for purposes of determining the &#8220;Compensation Actually Paid&#8221; are consistent with the methodology used for calculating the grant date fair value for financial reporting purposes. </div></td></tr></table><div style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="text-align:start; BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%">

<td style="width:2%">&#160;</td>

<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; font-size: 8pt; font-family: ARIAL; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;"><ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:NamedExecutiveOfficersFnTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-8691">For fiscal 2024, our <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEOs were Mark Robinson, Nir Patel, and Daniel Moore. Hamlin, Chris R. Homeister, and Daniel J. Kaufman.</ix:nonNumeric> </div></td></tr></table><div style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</div>

<td style="width:2%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(4)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; font-size: 8pt; font-family: ARIAL; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;"><ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:PeerGroupIssuersFnTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-8704">The Company Total Shareholder Return (&#8220;TSR&#8221;) and the Company&#8217;s Peer Group TSR reflected in these columns for each applicable fiscal year is calculated based on a fixed investment of $100 at the applicable measurement point on the same cumulative basis as is used in Item 201(e) of Regulation <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">S-K,</div> assuming an initial investment date of January&#160;31, 2020. The peer group used to determine the Company&#8217;s Peer Group TSR for each applicable fiscal year is the Dow Jones Specialty Retailers Index.</ix:nonNumeric> </div></td></tr></table><div style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</div>

<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(5)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; font-size: 8pt; font-family: ARIAL; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;">Represents the amount of net income (<div style="letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">loss</div>), as reflected in the Company&#8217;s audited financial statements for the fiscal year indicated. </div></td></tr></table><div style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="text-align:start; BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:2%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(6)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; font-size: 8pt; font-family: ARIAL; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;">For purposes of this table, <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:CoSelectedMeasureName" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" id="ixv-10308">United States Operating Profit (excluding royalties)</ix:nonNumeric>, which was first used as a measure in our executive compensation program for fiscal 2024 and tracked by the Company beginning in fiscal 2022, is defined as operating earnings (loss) for the United States segment less deductions for intercompany and other items, including intercompany royalties and foreign currency translation adjustments, and additions for certain <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-cash</div> and <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">one-time</div> items, including asset impairment charges. For fiscal 2021 and 2020, amounts in this table reflect United States operating earnings (loss) as reported in the Company&#8217;s Form <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">10-K.</div> </div></td></tr></table><div style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</div><ix:exclude>

<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;white-space:nowrap;vertical-align:bottom;background-color:#000000"><div style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">)</div></td></tr></table></ix:continuation></ix:nonNumeric></ix:nonNumeric><ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:TabularListTableTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-8957"><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">Tabular List of Most Important Financial Performance Measures </div></div></div></div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">For fiscal 2024, <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:MeasureName" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025_1TypedMemberecdMeasureAxis" id="ixv-10323">United States Operating Profit (excluding royalties)</ix:nonNumeric> and the Company stock price were the only financial performance measures that the Company used to tie CAP to our <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEOs to Company Performance. </div></ix:nonNumeric> <div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="display:inline;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">Pay Versus Performance Narrative Disclosure </div></div></div></div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Overall, our CAP tracked very closely with our stock price, which has primarily driven the fluctuations in our CAP values as shown above. CAP to George Sherman and our <div style="white-space:nowrap;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEOs in fiscal 2020 was significantly higher than the Summary Compensation Table (&#8220;SCT&#8221;) total due to the high volatility in our stock price at the end of fiscal 2020. In fiscal 2021 and 2022, CAP to both of our PEOs and our <div style="white-space:nowrap;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEOs was lower than the SCT total, and lower than the respective CAP values in fiscal 2020, due to our less volatile stock price performance over these fiscal years since the end of fiscal 2020. In fiscal 2023, tracking with our stock price, CAP to Matthew Furlong and to our <div style="white-space:nowrap;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEOs was lower than the SCT total. While Mark Robinson served as PEO from June&#160;7, 2023 to September&#160;28, 2023, his CAP was generally aligned with other <div style="white-space:nowrap;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEOs in fiscal 2023. In fiscal 2023 and 2024 for Ryan Cohen, SCT and CAP are equal given Ryan Cohen does not receive any compensation from the Company (apart from the $269,000 Cohen received in fiscal 2024 as a reimbursement for security services), while CAP to our <div style="white-space:nowrap;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEOs in fiscal 2024 was lower than the SCT mainly due to one <div style="white-space:nowrap;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEO forfeiting equity upon leaving the Company (otherwise CAP would have been greater than the SCT values due to our stock price performance in fiscal 2024). </div><ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:TotalShareholderRtnVsPeerGroupTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-8975"><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The increase in our stock <div style="display:inline;">price </div>that contributed significantly to the CAP in fiscal 2020 also drove our Total Shareholder Return (&#8220;TSR&#8221;) through the end of fiscal 2024. Our TSR has significantly outperformed our Peer Group TSR during this period, as shown in the table above. Specifically, our TSR performed significantly better than our Peer Group TSR through the end of fiscal 2020. After a meaningful increase in fiscal 2020, our TSR performance was negative in fiscal 2021, 2022, and 2023, before increasing again in fiscal 2024. Over the full five-year period, both our TSR and Peer Group TSR was positive, and our TSR performance meaningfully outperformed our Peer Group in total. </div></ix:nonNumeric> <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:CompActuallyPaidVsTotalShareholderRtnTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-8978"><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The close relationship between TSR and CAP was evident across the fiscal years in the table above. Our CAP at the end of fiscal 2020 significantly increased as a direct result of our strong TSR through the end of fiscal 2020. Through fiscal 2021, our TSR decreased (although still greater than the initial fixed $100 investment), and the CAP to our NEOs significantly declined year-over-year (except for Matthew Furlong, who joined the Company in fiscal 2021), and declined relative to fiscal 2021 SCT totals. In fiscal 2022, our TSR decreased slightly, which led to our CAP values declining relative to fiscal 2022 SCT totals (although CAP remained positive given the year-over-year TSR decline through fiscal 2022 was not significant). Through fiscal 2023 our TSR decreased, and as a result, CAP values to Matthew Furlong and <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEO CAP declined relative to fiscal 2023 SCT totals. As of the end of fiscal 2024 our CAP for <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEOs was once again lower than fiscal 2024 SCT totals, despite TSR increasing, mainly due to one <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">non-PEO</div> NEO forfeiting equity upon leaving the Company. </div></ix:nonNumeric> <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:CompActuallyPaidVsNetIncomeTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" continuedAt="TextSelection_139752559" id="ixv-8983"><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Our net income (loss) was not strongly correlated with CAP given a large portion of our executive compensation program is granted in equity, thereby directly tied to our stock price performance. In fiscal 2020, our net income was ($215 million) and the CAP <div style="display:inline;">values</div> </div><div style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</div></ix:nonNumeric>

<img alt="LOGO" src="g894376g85t00.jpg" style="width:0.740425in;height:0.149171in"/> </div></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap;text-align:right"><div style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1pt; font-size: 12pt; font-family: ARIAL; text-align: right; line-height: normal;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">2025&#160;Proxy&#160;Statement&#8201;|&#8201;<div style="color: rgb(226, 35, 26); letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">35</div></div></div></td></tr></table></div></div><div style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always"></div><hr style="color:#999999;height:3px;width:100%;clear:both"/><div style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold; margin-top: 1.67em; margin-bottom: 1.67em;"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></div><div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto"><ix:continuation id="TextSelection_139752559"><div style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">to our <div style="display:inline;">NEOs </div>were the highest over the full five-year period. In fiscal 2021, our net income decreased to ($<ix:nonFraction name="us-gaap:NetIncomeLoss" contextRef="P01_31_2021To01_29_2022" unitRef="Unit_USD" decimals="-6" scale="6" sign="-" format="ixt:num-dot-decimal" id="ixv-10324">381</ix:nonFraction> million) which was also aligned with a decrease in CAP over this period. In fiscal 2022, our net income increased to ($<ix:nonFraction name="us-gaap:NetIncomeLoss" contextRef="P01_30_2022To01_28_2023" unitRef="Unit_USD" decimals="-6" scale="6" sign="-" format="ixt:num-dot-decimal" id="ixv-10325">313</ix:nonFraction> million) aligning with the increase in CAP over this period. In fiscal 2023 and 2024, our significant growth in net <div style="letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">income</div> to $<ix:nonFraction name="us-gaap:NetIncomeLoss" contextRef="P01_29_2023To02_03_2024" unitRef="Unit_USD" decimals="-6" scale="6" format="ixt:num-dot-decimal" id="ixv-10326">7</ix:nonFraction> million and $<ix:nonFraction name="us-gaap:NetIncomeLoss" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" unitRef="Unit_USD" decimals="-6" scale="6" format="ixt:num-dot-decimal" id="ixv-10327">131</ix:nonFraction> million, respectively, was not correlated with CAP to our NEOs given CAP values decreased over the period. </div></ix:continuation><ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:CompActuallyPaidVsCoSelectedMeasureTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-9011"><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">For fiscal years 2020 through 2023, we did not have a company selected measure <div style="display:inline;">because </div>the Company did not use any financial performance measures to link fiscal years 2020 through 2023 executive compensation to company performance. In fiscal 2024, given we used United States Operating Profit (excluding royalties) as performance criteria in our Short-Term Equity Incentive program, we&#8217;ve included this measure as our company selected measure. Similar to net income (loss), our US Operating Profit (excluding royalties) was not strongly correlated with CAP. In fiscal 2024 our United States Operating Profit (excluding royalties) was $<ix:nonFraction name="ecd:CoSelectedMeasureAmt" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" unitRef="Unit_USD" decimals="-6" scale="6" format="ixt:num-dot-decimal" id="ixv-10328">24</ix:nonFraction> million, an increase from ($<ix:nonFraction name="ecd:CoSelectedMeasureAmt" contextRef="P01_29_2023To02_03_2024" unitRef="Unit_USD" decimals="-6" scale="6" sign="-" format="ixt:num-dot-decimal" id="ixv-10329">65</ix:nonFraction> million) in fiscal 2023. This significant growth <div style="letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">was</div> not correlated with CAP to our NEO&#8217;s given CAP values decreased over the period. </div></ix:nonNumeric> <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:AwardTmgMnpiDiscTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-9015"><div id="toc894376_31" style="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; font-size: 12pt; font-family: ARIAL;"><div style="font-weight:bold;display:inline;">Equity Grant Practices </div></div><div style="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div><div style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify"><div style="letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">The Company does not currently grant stock option awards or stock appreciation right <div style="display:inline;">awards</div></div>. </div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">During the last completed fiscal year, the Company did not make any stock option awards to our executive <div style="display:inline;">officers </div>within the <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">four-business-day</div> period before or the <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;"><div style="white-space:nowrap;display:inline;">one-business-day</div></div> period after the filing of any Form <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">10-K,</div> <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">10-Q,</div> or <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">8-K</div> containing material nonpublic information (as defined in Item 402(x)). Accordingly, no tabular disclosure under Item 402(x)(2)(ii) is required. </div><div style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify"><ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:AwardTmgPredtrmndFlag" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" format="ixt:fixed-true" id="ixv-9031">The Compensation Committee does not coordinate the timing of option grants with the release of material nonpublic information. Equity awards are typically granted on <div style="white-space: nowrap; letter-spacing: 0px; top: 0px;display:inline;">pre-determined</div> meeting dates of the Compensation Committee, and are subject to the Company&#8217;s Insider Trading Policy, which prohibits trading (and awards) when material nonpublic information is known to the participant or the Company.</ix:nonNumeric> <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:AwardTmgMethodTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-10330"><ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:AwardTmgHowMnpiCnsdrdTextBlock" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" escape="true" id="ixv-10331">All awards are granted with an exercise price equal to the average closing market price for the previous 30 trading days prior to the date of grant. The Company does <ix:nonNumeric name="ecd:MnpiDiscTimedForCompValFlag" contextRef="P02_04_2024To02_01_2025" format="ixt:fixed-false" id="ixv-10332">not time</ix:nonNumeric> the public disclosure of material nonpublic information to affect executive compensation outcomes.</ix:nonNumeric></ix:nonNumeric> </div><div style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</div></ix:nonNumeric>

<td style="padding-bottom:3pt ;vertical-align:top"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#8194;Equity compensation plans approved by security holders<sup style="font-size:75%; vertical-align:top">(3)</sup></p></td>

<h5 style="font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:16pt;width:100%;border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto">


<tr>

<td/>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:1%"/>
<td style="width:98%"/></tr>


<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:16pt">
<td style="vertical-align:top;white-space:nowrap" id="toc894376_33"><span style="font-weight:bold">PROPOSAL&#8201;3:</span></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.63em; font-size:16pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold"><span style="color:#e2231a">RATIFICATION OF APPOINTMENT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM </span></p></td></tr>
</table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Audit Committee has selected KPMG as the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accounting firm to audit the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements as of and for the year ended January&#160;31, 2026 (fiscal 2025) and the Company&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting as of January&#160;31, 2026. Although the Audit Committee has the sole authority to appoint the independent registered public accounting firm, as a matter of good corporate governance, we are submitting our selection of KPMG for ratification by the stockholders at the annual meeting. If the stockholders do not ratify the appointment of KPMG, the Audit Committee will reconsider the appointment. A representative of KPMG is expected to be present at the annual meeting, will have the opportunity to make a statement and is expected to be available to respond to appropriate questions. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Prior to the appointment of KPMG, Deloitte&#160;&amp; Touche LLP (&#8220;Deloitte&#8221;) served as our independent registered public accounting firm. For additional information, see &#8220;Change in Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm&#8221; below. We do not expect that a representative of Deloitte will be present at the Annual Meeting. </p> <p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">THE BOARD CONSIDERS KPMG TO BE WELL-QUALIFIED AND UNANIMOUSLY RECOMMENDS THAT STOCKHOLDERS VOTE <span style="text-decoration:underline">FOR</span> THE RATIFICATION OF THE AUDIT COMMITTEE&#8217;S APPOINTMENT OF KPMG AS OUR INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM FOR FISCAL 2025. PROXIES SOLICITED BY THIS PROXY STATEMENT WILL BE VOTED <span style="text-decoration:underline">FOR</span> THIS PROPOSAL UNLESS A VOTE AGAINST THE PROPOSAL OR ABSTENTION IS SPECIFICALLY INDICATED. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_34">Change in Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm </p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">On December&#160;6, 2024, after completing a competitive proposal process, the Audit Committee selected KPMG as the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accounting firm for fiscal 2025. This process also resulted in the effective dismissal of Deloitte as the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accounting firm. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Deloitte&#8217;s dismissal took effect following the completion of its audit and the issuance of its report on the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements and internal control over financial reporting for the Company&#8217;s fiscal year ending February&#160;1, 2025, which was included in the Company&#8217;s Annual Report on Form <span style="white-space:nowrap">10-K</span> filed with the SEC on March&#160;25, 2025. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Deloitte&#8217;s reports on the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements as of and for the fiscal years ended January&#160;28, 2023, February&#160;3, 2024 and February&#160;1, 2025 did not contain any adverse opinion or disclaimer of opinion, nor were they qualified or modified as to uncertainty, audit scope, or accounting principles. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">During the fiscal years ended January&#160;28, 2023, February&#160;3, 2024, and February&#160;1, 2025 there were: (i)&#160;no disagreements within the meaning of Item 304(a)(1)(iv) of Regulation <span style="white-space:nowrap">S-K</span> and the related instructions between the Company and Deloitte on any matters of accounting principles or practices, financial statement disclosure, or auditing scope or procedure which, if not resolved to Deloitte&#8217;s satisfaction, would have caused Deloitte to make reference thereto in their reports; and (ii)&#160;no &#8220;reportable events&#8221; within the meaning of Item 304(a)(1)(v) of Regulation <span style="white-space:nowrap">S-K.</span> </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Company requested that Deloitte furnish a letter addressed to the Securities and Exchange Commission stating whether or not it agrees with the above statements. A copy of Deloitte&#8217;s letter, dated December&#160;10, 2024, is filed as Exhibit 16.1 to our Form <span style="white-space:nowrap">8-K</span> filed with the SEC on December&#160;10, 2024. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">During the fiscal years ended January&#160;28, 2023, February&#160;3, 2024, and February&#160;1, 2025, neither the Company nor anyone on its behalf has consulted with KPMG regarding: (i)&#160;the application of accounting principles to a specific transaction, either completed or proposed, or the type of audit opinion that might be rendered on the Company&#8217;s financial statements, and neither a written report nor oral advice was provided to the Company that KPMG concluded was an important factor considered by the Company in reaching a decision as to any accounting, auditing, or financial reporting issue; (ii)&#160;any matter that was the subject of a disagreement within the meaning of Item 304(a)(1)(iv) of Regulation <span style="white-space:nowrap">S-K</span> and the related instructions; or (iii)&#160;any reportable event within the meaning of Item 304(a)(1)(v) of Regulation <span style="white-space:nowrap">S-K.</span> </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_35">Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm </p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">As described more fully in &#8220;Ratification of Appointment of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm&#8212;Proposal 3&#8221; above, the Audit Committee has selected KPMG as the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accounting firm for fiscal 2025, effectively dismissing Deloitte as the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accounting firm, which had served as the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accounting firm since 2013. </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;width:1%"/>
<td style="width:98%"/></tr>

<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap"> <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold"><span style="color:#e2231a">38</span>&#8201;|&#8201;2025&#160;Proxy&#160;Statement</p></td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:bottom;white-space:nowrap;text-align:right"> <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:1pt;text-align:right">


<img src="g894376g85t00.jpg" alt="LOGO" style="width:0.740425in;height:0.149171in"/>

<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The independent registered public accounting firm examines the annual financial statements and provides other permissible <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</span> and <span style="white-space:nowrap">tax-related</span> services for us. Management and the Audit Committee have considered the <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</span> services provided by KPMG and Deloitte and concluded they are compatible with maintaining the independence of those firms in their audit of the Company and in accordance with the SEC&#8217;s rules. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The following table sets forth information regarding fees for professional services rendered by Deloitte in fiscal 2024 and 2023: </p> <p style="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(1)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Audit Fees for services rendered by Deloitte in fiscal 2024 and 2023 include professional services for the audit of our annual financial statements and financial statement schedules, for the audit of our effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting, for reviews of our financial statements included in our quarterly reports on Form <span style="white-space:nowrap">10-Q</span> filed with the SEC, for professional services provided in connection with statutory and regulatory filings and for other consultations concerning financial accounting and reporting standards. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

No such fees were charged in fiscal 2023 or fiscal 2024. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left">(3)</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Tax Fees for services rendered by Deloitte in fiscal 2024 and 2023 included professional services for domestic and international tax compliance and tax planning and advice. Fees for fiscal 2023 include consultations involving tax considerations related to our NFT marketplace. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_36"><span style="white-space:nowrap">Pre-approval</span> Policies and Procedures </p> <p style="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Audit Committee Charter requires that, among other things, the Audit Committee <span style="white-space:nowrap">pre-approve</span> the rendering by our independent registered public accounting firm of all audit and permissible <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</span> services. Accordingly, the Audit Committee considers and <span style="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</span> any such audit and permissible <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</span> services on a <span style="white-space:nowrap"><span style="white-space:nowrap">case-by-case</span></span> basis or through the adoption of preapproval policies and procedures. The Audit Committee approved all of the services provided by Deloitte referred to above. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_37">Audit Committee Matters </p> <p style="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_38"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Primary Responsibilities and Fiscal 2024 Actions </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:4pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Audit Committee assists the Board in fulfilling its oversight responsibility and reviews the adequacy and integrity of our financial statements, financial reporting process and internal system of accounting controls; the appointment, termination, compensation, retention and oversight of the independent registered public accountants; the scope of the audit performed by the independent registered public accounting firm of our books and records; the internal audit function and plan; our compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; our Code of Business Conduct and Ethics; and, with management and the independent auditor, any related party transactions and approves such transactions, if any. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">For fiscal 2024, in fulfillment of its responsibilities, among other things, the Audit Committee: </p> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:4%">&#160;</td>
<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">Met with the senior members of our financial management team at each regularly scheduled meeting. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>
<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;border-spacing:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">

<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">Held separate private sessions, during its regularly scheduled meetings, with senior members of our financial management team, with the independent auditors, with representatives of internal audit and on its own, at which candid discussions regarding financial management, accounting, auditing and internal control issues took place. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

<td style="width:3%;vertical-align:top;text-align:left"><span style="color:#e2231a">&#8226;</span></td>
<td style="width:1%;vertical-align:top">&#160;</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;text-align:left"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt;text-align:justify">Participated with representatives of management and of the independent auditors in additional discussions as requested by the Audit Committee on areas of our operations. </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" id="toc894376_39"><span style="color:#e2231a"><span style="font-weight:bold">Report of the Audit Committee </span></span></p> <p style="margin-top:4pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Roles and Responsibilities </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The role of the Audit Committee is to assist the Board in its oversight of our financial reporting process. Management has the primary responsibility for the financial statements and the reporting process, including the system of internal controls over financial reporting. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Our independent registered public accounting firm is responsible for auditing our financial statements and its internal control over financial reporting, in accordance with the standards of the PCAOB, and expressing opinions as to the conformity of the financial statements with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States and the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting. The Audit Committee is responsible for the appointment, compensation and oversight of the work of our independent registered public accounting firm. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Required Disclosures and Discussions </p> <p style="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">In the performance of its oversight function, the Audit Committee has reviewed and discussed with management and the independent auditors the Company&#8217;s audited financial statements. The Audit Committee has also discussed with the independent auditors the matters required to be discussed by Auditing Standard No.&#160;1301, as adopted by the PCAOB, relating to communications with audit committees. In addition, the Audit Committee has received from the independent auditors the written disclosures and letter required by the applicable requirements of the PCAOB regarding the independent auditors&#8217; communications with the audit committee concerning independence, has discussed with the independent auditors their independence from us and our management, and has considered whether the independent auditors&#8217; provision of <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</span> services to us is compatible with maintaining the firm&#8217;s independence. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Audit Committee discussed with our internal auditors and the independent auditors the overall scope and plans for their respective audits. The internal auditors are responsible for preparing an annual audit plan and conducting internal audits under the control of our Head of Internal Audit, who is accountable to the Audit Committee. The Audit Committee met with the internal auditors and the independent auditors, with and without management present, to discuss the results of their examinations, their evaluations of our internal controls and the overall quality of our financial reporting. In addition, the Audit Committee met with our Principal Financial Officer and members of our management of finance and accounting to discuss the processes that they have undertaken to evaluate the accuracy and fair presentation of our financial statements and the effectiveness of our systems of disclosure controls and procedures and internal control over financial reporting. </p>
 <p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&#160;</p>

<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">
 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Committee Recommends Including the Financial Statements in the Annual Report </p> <p style="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Based on the reviews and discussions referred to above, the Audit Committee recommended to the Board, and the Board approved, that our audited consolidated financial statements be included in our 2024 Annual Report to Stockholders and in our Annual Report on Form <span style="white-space:nowrap">10-K</span> for our fiscal year ended February&#160;1, 2025 for filing with the SEC. </p> <p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Audit Committee: </p> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Jim Grube, Chair </p> <p style="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Alan Attal </p> <p style="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Yang Xu </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_40">Delinquent Section&#160;16(a) Reports </p> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Section&#160;16(a) of the Exchange Act requires our executive officers and directors, and persons who own more than ten percent of a registered class of our equity securities, to file initial statements of beneficial ownership (Form 3) and statements of changes in beneficial ownership (Forms 4 and 5) of common stock of the Company with the SEC. Executive officers, directors and greater than <span style="white-space:nowrap">ten-percent</span> stockholders are required to furnish us with copies of all such forms they file. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Based solely on our review of the copies of such forms received by us, or written representations from certain reporting persons that no additional forms were required, we believe that all filing requirements applicable to our executive officers, directors and greater than <span style="white-space:nowrap">ten-percent</span> stockholders were complied with for the fiscal year ended February&#160;1, 2025, except that, due to administrative errors: (i)&#160;a Form 3 was not filed within the required period for the appointment to the Board for director Nat Turner, filed on December&#160;5, 2024, and (ii)&#160;a Form 4 was not filed within the required period for one transaction for Daniel Moore, our Principal Financial and Accounting Officer, reporting the sale of shares, filed on October&#160;10, 2024. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_41">Certain Relationships and Related Transactions </p> <p style="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The Audit Committee Charter requires the Audit Committee to review with management and the independent registered public accountants and approve all transactions and courses of dealing with parties related to us. This obligation of the Audit Committee is described earlier in this Proxy Statement in the &#8220;Election of Directors&#8221; section, which states that the Audit Committee is responsible for reviewing and approving related party transactions. Also, as described earlier in this Proxy Statement in the &#8220;Election of Directors&#8221; section, the Company has adopted a Code of Ethics for Senior Financial and Executive Officers and a Code of Standards, Ethics and Conduct applicable to the Company&#8217;s management-level employees. The codes require that all of our employees and directors avoid conflicts of interest, defined as situations where the person&#8217;s private interests interfere in any way, or even appear to interfere, with our interests as a whole. In addition, at least annually each director and executive officer completes a detailed questionnaire that inquires about any business relationship that may give rise to a conflict of interest and all transactions in which we are involved and in which the executive officer, a director or a related person has a direct or indirect material interest. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">It is our policy that any potential conflict of interest transaction with an executive officer or director or any transaction that triggers disclosure under Item 404(a) of Regulation <span style="white-space:nowrap">S-K</span> as a result of these inquiries is required to be reviewed and approved or ratified by the Audit Committee. Except as described below, during fiscal 2024, there were no transactions requiring disclosure with, or with an immediate family member of, directors, NEOs or persons who were the beneficial owners of more than 5% of our outstanding shares during the fiscal year. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">In November 2024, the Company entered into a collaboration with Collectors through PSA, whereby the Company would become an authorized PSA dealer, and PSA would provide authentication and grading services for trading cards through select Company stores across the United States. Mr.&#160;Turner, a director of the Company, is the Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of Collectors. Mr.&#160;Turner also owns up to a 10% equity interest in PSA and has been awarded additional unvested equity compensation awards at Collectors, which are subject to forfeiture if certain performance conditions are not satisfied. During fiscal 2024, the approximate dollar value of the transactions between GameStop and PSA pursuant to the collaboration agreement was $9.8 million. In accordance with the Company&#8217;s policy, the Audit Committee reviewed, and provided prior approval of, such transaction and determined that such transaction was in the best interest of the Company and its stockholders. </p>

 <p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:16pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold" id="toc894376_42">OTHER MATTERS </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We do not intend to present any other business for action at the annual meeting and do not know of any other business intended to be presented by others. If any matters other than the matters described in the Notice of Annual Meeting of Stockholders and this Proxy Statement should be presented for stockholder action at the annual meeting, it is the intention of the persons designated in the proxy to vote thereon in accordance with their best judgment. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Financial and Other Information </p> <p style="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">We are furnishing our Annual Report for the fiscal year ended February&#160;1, 2025, including consolidated financial statements, together with this Proxy Statement. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Cautionary Statement Regarding Forward Looking Statements </p> <p style="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">This Proxy Statement contains forward-looking statements within the meaning of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. Such statements may include, but are not limited to, statements related to risks associated with our compensation programs, our future performance, our plans, objectives, expectations and intentions, and other statements that are not historical facts. Such statements are based upon the current beliefs and expectations of our management and are subject to significant risks and uncertainties. Actual results may differ from those set forth in the forward-looking statements. We undertake no obligation to publicly update or revise any forward-looking statements except as required by law. Factors that may cause actual results to differ materially from those contemplated by the statements in this Proxy Statement can be found in our most recent Annual Report filed with the SEC on March&#160;25, 2025. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Proposals Pursuant to Rule <span style="white-space:nowrap">14a-8</span> </p> <p style="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Proposals of stockholders pursuant to Rule <span style="white-space:nowrap">14a-8</span> of the Exchange Act intended to be presented for inclusion in our proxy materials for the annual meeting of stockholders to be held in 2026 must meet the requirements under Rule <span style="white-space:nowrap">14a-8</span> and be received by the Secretary, at GameStop Corp., 625 Westport Parkway, Grapevine, Texas 76051, no later than December&#160;31, 2025. However, if the date of the 2026 annual meeting is more than 30 days before or after June&#160;12, 2026, then the deadline for submitting any stockholder proposal for inclusion in the proxy materials relating to such annual meeting will be a reasonable time before we begin to print and mail such proxy materials. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Proxy Access Director Nominees </p> <p style="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Under the proxy access provisions of our Bylaws, stockholders are entitled to nominate and include in our proxy materials director nominees, provided that the eligibility and procedural requirements specified in our Bylaws, including advance notice requirements, are satisfied. The notice must be delivered to the Secretary at our principal executive offices, at 625 Westport Parkway, Grapevine, Texas 76051, not less than 120 days nor more than 150 days prior to the first anniversary of the date on which we first mailed our Proxy Statement or a notice of availability of our Proxy Statement (whichever is earlier) in connection with the most recent annual meeting of stockholder. As a result, any notice given by a stockholder pursuant to the proxy access provisions of our Bylaws with respect to the 2026 annual meeting must be received no earlier than the close of business on December&#160;1, 2025, and no later than the close of business on December&#160;31, 2025. However, in the event that the date of the 2026 annual meeting is more than 30 days before June&#160;12, 2026 or more than 60 days after June&#160;12, 2026, then the notice, to be timely, must be delivered not earlier than the close of business on the 120th day prior to the date of the 2026 annual meeting and not later than the close of business on the later of (x)&#160;the 90th day prior to the date of the 2026 annual meeting or (y)&#160;the 10th day following the day of the first public announcement of the date of the 2026 annual meeting. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">The complete requirements for submitting a nominee for inclusion in our proxy materials are set forth in our Bylaws, a copy of which can be obtained upon request directed to the Secretary at our principal executive offices at the address set forth above or on our website at <span style="font-style:italic"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><span style="font-family:ARIAL;color:#1e3aff">http://investor.gamestop.com/corporate-governance</span></span>.</span> </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Other Proposals and Nominees </p> <p style="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">Any stockholder who wishes to propose any business to be considered by the stockholders at the 2026 annual meeting or who wants to nominate a person for election to the Board at that meeting, other than (i)&#160;a proposal for inclusion in the Proxy Statement pursuant to Rule <span style="white-space:nowrap">14a-8</span> or (ii)&#160;pursuant to the proxy access Bylaw provisions, in each case as described above, must provide a written notice that sets forth the specified information described in our Bylaws concerning the proposed business or nominee. To be timely, a stockholder&#8217;s notice must be delivered to or mailed and received at our principal executive offices not less than 90 days nor more than 120 days prior to the first anniversary date of our immediately preceding annual meeting, which, with respect to the 2026 </p>

However, in the event that the date of the 2026 annual meeting is more than 25 days before or after June&#160;12, 2026, then the notice, to be timely, must be delivered not later than the close of business on the tenth day following the date on which the notice of the date of the meeting is mailed or publicly announced. In addition to the requirements contained in our Bylaws, to comply with the universal proxy rules, stockholders who intend to solicit proxies in support of director nominees other than our nominees must provide notice that sets forth the information required by Rule <span style="white-space:nowrap">14a-19</span> under the Exchange Act no later than April&#160;13, 2026 (the 60th day prior to the first anniversary of the annual meeting for the preceding year&#8217;s annual meeting). </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">Householding of Proxy Materials </p> <p style="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p><div style="line-height:1.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #e2231a">&#160;</div> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;text-align:justify">SEC rules permit companies and intermediaries such as brokers to satisfy delivery requirements with respect to two or more stockholders sharing the same address by delivering a single annual report and proxy statement or a single Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials addressed to those stockholders. This process, which is commonly referred to as &#8220;householding&#8221;, can reduce the volume of duplicate information received at households. While the Company does not household, a number of brokerage firms with account holders have instituted householding. Once a stockholder has consented or receives notice from their broker that the broker will be householding materials to the stockholder&#8217;s address, householding will continue until the stockholder is notified otherwise or until one or more of the stockholders revokes their consent. If your annual report and proxy statement have been househeld and you wish to receive separate copies of these documents now and/or in the future, or if your household is receiving multiple copies of these documents and you wish to request that future deliveries be limited to a single copy, you may notify your broker. You can also request and we will promptly deliver a separate copy of the proxy materials by: writing to our Secretary, GameStop Corp., 625 Westport Parkway, Grapevine, Texas 76051; or by telephoning (817) <span style="white-space:nowrap">424-2000.</span> </p> <p style="margin-top:20pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL;font-weight:bold">STOCKHOLDERS ARE URGED TO SUBMIT THEIR PROXY CARDS WITHOUT DELAY. A PROMPT RESPONSE WILL BE GREATLY APPRECIATED. </p>

 </p> <p style="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:0.5pt"><span style="color:#FFFFFF">MEETING DETAILSThe Annual Meeting of Stockholders of GameStop Corp. will be held on June&#160;12, 2025 at 10:00 a.m. (Central Daylight Time) virtually at meetnow.global/MGWWKKP.Proposals to be voted on at the meeting are listed below along with the Board of Directors&#8217; recommendations.THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS RECOMMENDS A VOTE FOR ALL THE NOMINEES LISTED:1. Elect five directors, each to serve as a member of the Board of Directors until the next annual meeting of stockholders and until such irector&#8217;s successor is elected and qualified:01&#8212;Ryan Cohen 02&#8212;Alain (Alan) Attal 03&#8212;Lawrence (Larry) Cheng04&#8212;James (Jim) Grube 05&#8212;Nathaniel (Nat) TurnerTHE BOARD OF DIRECTORS RECOMMENDS A VOTE FOR PROPOSALS 2 AND 3:2. Provide an advisory, <span style="white-space:nowrap">non-binding</span> vote on the compensation of our named executive officers.3. Ratify our Audit Committee&#8217;s appointment of KPMG LLP as our independent registered public accounting firm for our fiscal year ending January&#160;31, 2026.OTHER BUSINESS:4. Transact such other business, if any, as may properly come before the annual meeting and at any postponement or adjournment of the annual meeting.PLEASE NOTE: YOU CANNOT VOTE BY RETURNING THIS NOTICETo vote your shares you must go online or request a paper copy of the proxy materials to receive a proxy card.ORDER MATERIALSPlease make your materials request by using one of the methods listed below. You will need the number located in the box on the reverse side.REQUEST VIA:Internet Visit https://www.investorvote.com/GME Phone Call <span style="white-space:nowrap"><span style="white-space:nowrap"><span style="white-space:nowrap">1-866-641-4276Email</span></span></span> Send an email to investorvote@computershare.com and include:&#8226; &#8220;Proxy Materials GameStop Corp.&#8221; in the subject line&#8226; Your full name and address&#8226; The number located in the white circle on the reverse side&#8226; Statement that you want a paper copy of the meeting materialsPLEASE REVIEW THE MEETING MATERIALSWe encourage you to read the meeting documents found at http://investor.gamestop.com. </span></p>
